+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "markdown",
+      "metadata": {},
+      "source": [
+        "## 1. Generate SFT Data\n",
+        "\n",
+        "\n",
+        "This step uses an external LLM (via OpenRouter) with a dedicated prompt to generate synthetic Dusty conversations. The prompt defines the robot vacuum persona, topics, and speaking style.\n",
+        "\n",
+        "**Models used:**\n",
+        "- **Primary:** `qwen/qwen3-235b-a22b-2507` (stronger Dusty-style responses)\n",
+        "- **Fallback:** `openai/gpt-oss-120b` (used if primary is unavailable)\n",
+        "\n",
+        "Both use the `:floor` suffix to route to the lowest-cost provider on OpenRouter. Override them with `DUSTY_MODEL` and `DUSTY_FALLBACK_MODEL`.\n",
+        "\n",
+        "**Before you start:**\n",
+        "- Set your OpenRouter API key as `OPENAI_API_KEY`\n",
+        "- If you change the persona, update the prompt and categories in `data_pipeline/generate_sft.py`\n",
+        "\n",
+        "**Cost:** The full dataset (500 examples per category, ~30k rows) cost us under $3 with Qwen. Start with 5 per category (as below) to check quality before scaling up."
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "code",
+      "execution_count": null,
+      "metadata": {},
+      "outputs": [],
+      "source": [
+        "# Optional: set your OpenRouter key before running this cell.\n",
+        "# import os\n",
+        "# os.environ[\"OPENAI_API_KEY\"] = \"...\"\n",
+        "\n",
+        "!make generate-sft DUSTY_SFT_PER_CATEGORY=5 DUSTY_SFT_BATCH_SIZE=5"
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "markdown",
+      "metadata": {},
+      "source": [
+        "### 1.1 Preview SFT Rows\n",
+        "\n",
+        "\n",
+        "Each JSONL row needs `category`, `user`, and `dusty`. The `category` field is metadata for filtering and balancing; training uses the user and assistant text."
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "code",
+      "execution_count": null,
+      "metadata": {},
+      "outputs": [],
+      "source": [
+        "import json\n",
+        "from pathlib import Path\n",
+        "\n",
+        "sft_path = Path(\"artifacts/datasets/dusty_sft.jsonl\")\n",
+        "with sft_path.open(\"r\", encoding=\"utf-8\") as file:\n",
+        "    for index, line in zip(range(5), file):\n",
+        "        row = json.loads(line)\n",
+        "        print(json.dumps(row, indent=2)[:800])\n",
+        "        print()"
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "markdown",
+      "metadata": {},
+      "source": [
+        "### 1.2 Filter and Balance SFT Data [Optional]\n",
+        "\n",
+        "\n",
+        "The model uses `max_seq_len=256` tokens. If a training conversation exceeds the limit, the tail gets truncated and the model never sees the `<eos>` (End of Sequence) token. Without learning when to emit `<eos>`, the model will generate endless, looping text during inference.\n",
+        "\n",
+        "The main way to keep examples short is to write the generation prompt so the LLM produces concise responses (2-3 sentences). Filtering is an optional safeguard: it drops any example whose answer exceeds `DUSTY_SFT_MAX_ANSWER_TOKENS` and samples a category-balanced subset. Use a smaller target for experiments and a larger target for final training."
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "code",
+      "execution_count": null,
+      "metadata": {},
+      "outputs": [],
+      "source": [
+        "!make filter-sft \\\n",
+        "  DUSTY_SFT_FILTER_TARGET=200 \\\n",
+        "  DUSTY_SFT_MAX_ANSWER_TOKENS=256 \\\n",
+        "  DUSTY_SFT_FILTERED_OUT=artifacts/datasets/dusty_sft_200.jsonl"
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "markdown",
+      "metadata": {},
+      "source": [
+        "## 2. Tokenizer Fertility\n",
+        "\n",
+        "\n",
+        "Fertility is tokens per whitespace-delimited word. For a tiny model, roughly `1.2` to `1.5` is usually a useful range. Higher values mean words are split heavily; lower values may spend too much of the model on embeddings.\n",
+        "\n",
+        "Vocabulary size is part of the model's parameter budget. A larger vocabulary increases the embedding and output projection matrices, which can make the checkpoint larger without making the transformer layers more capable. Fertility testing asks a practical question: if we spend more parameters on vocabulary, do we actually reduce token count enough to justify it?\n",
+        "\n",
+        "| Vocab Size | Lines | Words | Tokens | Fertility |\n",
+        "|-----------|------:|------:|------:|---------:|\n",
+        "| 4,096 | 10,000 | 327,204 | 430,793 | 1.317 |\n",
+        "| 8,192 | 10,000 | 327,204 | 410,990 | 1.256 |\n",
+        "\n",
+        "The table confirms the diminishing returns:\n",
+        "\n",
+        "- **4,096 tokens:** 1.32 fertility at a small parameter footprint\n",
+        "- **8,192 tokens:** 1.26 fertility, but adds roughly 4M embedding parameters\n",
+        "\n",
+        "For Dusty, moving from 4K to 8K did not produce a large enough improvement to justify the extra parameters, so the default tokenizer stays around 4K tokens."
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "code",
+      "execution_count": null,
+      "metadata": {},
+      "outputs": [],
+      "source": [
+        "!uv run python data_pipeline/test_tokenizer_fertility.py \\\n",
+        "  --input artifacts/datasets/tinystories_base.txt \\\n",
+        "  --training-files artifacts/datasets/tinystories_base.txt artifacts/datasets/dusty_pretrain.txt \\\n",
+        "  --lines 10000 \\\n",
+        "  --vocab-sizes 2048 4096 8192"
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "markdown",
+      "metadata": {},
+      "source": [
+        "## 3. Select Pretraining Checkpoints\n",
+        "\n",
+        "### 3.1 Evaluate Pretraining Checkpoints\n",
+        "\n",
+        "Before SFT, evaluate the base `dusty8m` checkpoints directly. The pretrained model was trained on TinyStories, so it should produce coherent story-like text but does not yet have the Dusty conversational personality."
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "code",
+      "execution_count": null,
+      "id": "c8753dd1",
+      "metadata": {},
+      "outputs": [],
+      "source": [
+        "!make generate PROFILE=dusty8m PROMPT=\"Deep in the forest there was a \" TOP_P=0.9 TEMPERATURE=0.8"
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "markdown",
+      "id": "95fed994",
+      "metadata": {},
+      "source": [
+        "### 3.2 Compare Pretraining Checkpoints\n",
+        "\n",
+        "\n",
+        "During pretraining, the loss curve does not tell the whole story. A model with a low loss might generate looping, repetitive text, while an earlier checkpoint produces perfectly readable English. Production pipelines run full benchmark suites to quantify this, but here we keep it simple with direct side-by-side reads.\n",
+        "\n",
+        "To find the best version of your base model, evaluate the generated text manually. Use `CHECKPOINT_STEP` to sample outputs from different intermediate checkpoints. Generate a short story from several steps and compare them for coherence, spelling, and repetition."
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "code",
+      "execution_count": null,
+      "id": "6d4bc02c",
+      "metadata": {},
+      "outputs": [],
+      "source": [
+        "# Use story-based cliffhangers to test the raw pre-trained base model\n",
+        "base_prompts = [\n",
+        "    \"Once upon a time,\",\n",
+        "    \"Lily was a little girl who loved to\",\n",
+        "    \"Deep in the forest, there lived a little boy named Timmy. One day, he\",\n",
+        "]\n",
+        "base_checkpoint_steps = [50, 100, 150]\n",
+        "\n",
+        "for step in base_checkpoint_steps:\n",
+        "    print(\"#\" * 80)\n",
+        "    print(\"BASE CHECKPOINT_STEP:\", step)\n",
+        "    for prompt in base_prompts:\n",
+        "        print(\"=\" * 80)\n",
+        "        print(\"PROMPT:\", prompt)\n",
+        "        !make generate PROFILE=dusty8m CHECKPOINT_STEP={step} PROMPT=\"{prompt}\" TOP_P=0.9 TEMPERATURE=0.8"
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "markdown",
+      "id": "c4f4d469",
+      "metadata": {},
+      "source": [
+        "Sampling these checkpoints serves two different purposes depending on where you are in the training cycle:\n",
+        "\n",
+        "- **Early Debugging (The Sanity Check)**\n",
+        "\n",
+        "    While the model is actively training, sample early steps to verify that it is progressively learning. Early checkpoints will show the model transition from pure noise to forming real letters to generating basic words. Keep Chinchilla scaling laws in mind - do not expect cohesive stories this early. You are simply confirming that the training pipeline is working.\n",
+        "\n",
+        "- **Finding the Golden Zone (Post-Training)**\n",
+        "\n",
+        "    Once training is complete and the model has seen enough tokens to satisfy the scaling laws, you enter the golden zone. If you choose to train all the way to the full 160 million token target, this region will be around steps 19,600 to 20,000.\n",
+        "\n",
+        "**Note on our run:** To keep this demonstration lightweight, we stopped our production pretraining run early at step 5,700 (~46M tokens). Even at this early fraction of the scaling law target, the model already produces remarkably cohesive English. If you have time to let training run to completion, we recommend exploring checkpoints in the 19,600+ golden zone to see how text quality and vocabulary diversity mature. Otherwise, step 5,700 is the target baseline for a functional model.\n",
+        "\n",
+        "Sample several checkpoints strictly within your chosen region and compare them. The best checkpoint is the one that produces the most natural-sounding text with the fewest spelling errors and the least amount of looping.\n"
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "markdown",
+      "id": "78a0ffdf",
+      "metadata": {},
+      "source": [
+        "### 3.3 Promote the Best Pretraining Checkpoint\n",
+        "\n",
+        "\n",
+        "Once you have evaluated your checkpoints and selected the winner from your pretraining run (whether it is the lightweight step 5,700 or a deeper checkpoint from the golden zone), you must **promote** it to be the official base model.\n",
+        "\n",
+        "The subsequent Supervised Fine-Tuning (SFT) phase is hardcoded to look for a specific base model file named `artifacts/checkpoints/dusty8m.pt`. To promote your best checkpoint, copy your chosen step file and rename it to this target filename.\n",
+        "\n",
+        "Run the following command to promote your chosen step (replace `5700` if you selected a different one):"
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "code",
+      "execution_count": null,
+      "id": "47a1cf2f",
+      "metadata": {},
+      "outputs": [],
+      "source": [
+        "!cp artifacts/checkpoints/dusty8m_step_5700.pt artifacts/checkpoints/dusty8m.pt"
+      ]
+    },
