+      "cell_type": "markdown",
+      "id": "f520b277",
+      "metadata": {},
+      "source": [
+        "**Sanity Check Your Base Model**\n",
+        "\n",
+        "After promoting the file, it is highly recommended to run one final sanity check. This ensures that you copied the correct checkpoint and that `dusty8m.pt` is successfully generating coherent English before you invest time into the fine-tuning phase.\n",
+        "\n",
+        "Run the generation command using the base profile to test your newly promoted model:"
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "code",
+      "execution_count": null,
+      "id": "4f47fe2e",
+      "metadata": {},
+      "outputs": [],
+      "source": [
+        "!make generate PROFILE=dusty8m PROMPT=\"Deep in the forest there was a\" TOP_P=0.9 TEMPERATURE=0.8"
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "markdown",
+      "metadata": {},
+      "source": [
+        "## 4. Select SFT Checkpoints\n",
+        "\n",
+        "### 4.1 Compare SFT Step Checkpoints\n",
+        "\n",
+        "\n",
+        "Loss is only a coarse signal for tiny character models. During training, step checkpoints such as `artifacts/checkpoints/dusty8m_sft_step_100.pt` let you evaluate intermediate model behavior. Generate the same fixed prompt set from several `CHECKPOINT_STEP` values and compare instruction following, persona consistency, repetition, and answer length.\n",
+        "\n",
+        "Unlike the pre-training phase, Supervised Fine-Tuning (SFT) does not follow Chinchilla scaling laws. Instead of aiming for hundreds of millions of tokens, SFT is simply about teaching the base model a specific conversational format and persona. For this repository, we use a custom 30k instruction dataset. We found that training for about 7 epochs (roughly 1,960 iterations, depending on your batch size) is the sweet spot.\n",
+        "\n",
+        "During SFT, the model can overfit to the chat format quickly. This is why you should stop relying purely on the loss curve and begin selecting checkpoints qualitatively by reading the generated text.\n",
+        "\n",
+        "When a step checkpoint behaves better than the final checkpoint, promote it by copying that file over the profile's default checkpoint path. After promotion, remove `CHECKPOINT_STEP` from the generation command; normal `make generate PROFILE=sft_dusty8m ...` will use the selected model."
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "markdown",
+      "id": "f732c7ca",
+      "metadata": {},
+      "source": [
+        "## 4.1 Compare SFT Checkpoints\n",
+        "\n",
+        "Just as we established during pre-training, the loss curve is only a coarse signal. However, what you are evaluating for during SFT is entirely different. Instead of checking for basic English coherence, you are testing for **instruction following, persona consistency, and appropriate answer length**.\n",
+        "\n",
+        "\n",
+        "Unlike pre-training, SFT does not follow Chinchilla scaling laws; you are simply teaching the model a specific conversational format. Because small models can quickly overfit to chat templates, qualitative testing is critical. For this repository, we use a custom 30k instruction dataset. We found that training for about 21 epochs (roughly 19,600 iterations with a batch size of 32) is the sweet spot.\n",
+        "\n",
+        "Sample intermediate checkpoints strictly within this region using `CHECKPOINT_STEP` to find the best persona fit."
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "code",
+      "execution_count": null,
+      "metadata": {},
+      "outputs": [],
+      "source": [
+        "prompts = [\n",
+        "    \"where are you?\",\n",
+        "    \"are you scared?\",\n",
+        "    \"what do you dream about?\",\n",
+        "]\n",
+        "\n",
+        "checkpoint_steps = [100, 500, 1000]  # Update these based on your runs\n",
+        "\n",
+        "for step in checkpoint_steps:\n",
+        "    print(\"#\" * 80)\n",
+        "    print(\"CHECKPOINT_STEP:\", step)\n",
+        "    for prompt in prompts:\n",
+        "        print(\"=\" * 80)\n",
+        "        print(\"PROMPT:\", prompt)\n",
+        "        !make generate PROFILE=sft_dusty8m CHECKPOINT_STEP={step} PROMPT=\"{prompt}\" TOP_P=0.9 TEMPERATURE=0.8"
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "markdown",
+      "metadata": {},
+      "source": [
+        "### 4.2 Promote the Selected SFT Checkpoint\n",
+        "\n",
+        "Exactly as you did with the base model, you must promote your winning checkpoint to finalize the pipeline. This copies your chosen step file and renames it to `artifacts/checkpoints/dusty8m_sft.pt`, which is the default weight for the `sft_dusty8m` profile used in the chat interface.\n",
+        "\n",
+        "Set `BEST_STEP` to the checkpoint step that produced the best qualitative behavior. Run the following commands to promote your model and perform a final sanity check (replace `19600` if you chose a different step):"
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "code",
+      "execution_count": null,
+      "metadata": {},
+      "outputs": [],
+      "source": [
+        "BEST_STEP = 19600\n",
+        "\n",
+        "!cp artifacts/checkpoints/dusty8m_sft_step_{BEST_STEP}.pt artifacts/checkpoints/dusty8m_sft.pt\n",
+        "\n",
+        "# This command intentionally omits CHECKPOINT_STEP. It now uses the promoted default checkpoint.\n",
+        "!make generate PROFILE=sft_dusty8m PROMPT=\"where are you?\" TOP_P=0.9 TEMPERATURE=0.8"
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "markdown",
+      "metadata": {},
+      "source": [
+        "## 5. Inference Internals\n",
+        "\n",
+        "### 5.1 Load an Inference Engine\n",
+        "\n",
+        "Use the local promoted SFT checkpoint if you trained one. If you skipped training, pre-trained checkpoints are available on Hugging Face Hub at `mkhordoo/dusty-8m-sft` and will be downloaded automatically when you run the cell below."
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "code",
+      "execution_count": null,
+      "id": "c8e7df77",
+      "metadata": {},
+      "outputs": [],
+      "source": [
+        "from pathlib import Path\n",
+        "import torch\n",
+        "from dustylm.inference import Inference\n",
+        "\n",
+        "checkpoint_path = Path(\"artifacts/checkpoints/dusty8m_sft.pt\")\n",
+        "tokenizer_path = Path(\"artifacts/tokenizers/dusty_tokenizer.json\")\n",
+        "\n",
+        "if not checkpoint_path.exists():\n",
+        "    from huggingface_hub import hf_hub_download\n",
+        "\n",
+        "    print(\"Local checkpoint not found, downloading from Hugging Face Hub...\")\n",
+        "    checkpoint_path = Path(\n",
+        "        hf_hub_download(repo_id=\"mkhordoo/dusty-8m-sft\", filename=\"dusty8m_sft.pt\")\n",
+        "    )\n",
+        "    tokenizer_path = Path(\n",
+        "        hf_hub_download(\n",
+        "            repo_id=\"mkhordoo/dusty-8m-sft\", filename=\"dusty_tokenizer.json\"\n",
+        "        )\n",
+        "    )\n",
+        "\n",
+        "engine = Inference(\n",
+        "    checkpoint_path=checkpoint_path,\n",
+        "    tokenizer_path=tokenizer_path,\n",
+        "    device=\"cuda\" if torch.cuda.is_available() else \"cpu\",\n",
+        ")\n",
+        "print(\"Profile:\", engine.profile_name)"
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "markdown",
+      "metadata": {},
+      "source": [
+        "### 5.2 Convenience Wrapper and CLI Chat\n",
+        "\n",
+        "\n",
+        "For scripts or demos, wrap the response dictionary and return only the generated assistant text. For a terminal chat loop, use `make chat`, which runs `uv run python -m dustylm.inference`."
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "code",
+      "execution_count": null,
+      "metadata": {},
+      "outputs": [],
+      "source": [
+        "def chat(prompt, *, max_tokens=128, temperature=0.8, top_p=0.8):\n",
+        "    response = engine.chat_completion(\n",
+        "        [{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": prompt}],\n",
+        "        max_tokens=max_tokens,\n",
+        "        temperature=temperature,\n",
+        "        top_p=top_p,\n",
+        "    )\n",
+        "    return response[\"choices\"][0][\"message\"][\"content\"].strip()\n",
+        "\n",
+        "\n",
+        "for prompt in [\n",
+        "    \"who are you?\",\n",
+        "    \"are you scared?\",\n",
+        "    \"what do you dream about?\",\n",
+        "]:\n",
+        "    print(f\"You> {prompt}\")\n",
+        "    print(f\"Dusty> {chat(prompt)}\\n\")"
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "markdown",
+      "metadata": {},
+      "source": [
+        "### 5.3 OpenAI-Style Chat Completion\n",
+        "\n",
+        "\n",
+        "`Inference.chat_completion()` accepts OpenAI-style `messages` and returns an OpenAI-like dictionary. That keeps local DustyLM inference close to common chat-completion calling patterns while still running against a local PyTorch checkpoint."
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "code",
+      "execution_count": null,
+      "metadata": {},
+      "outputs": [],
+      "source": [
+        "messages = [{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"where are you?\"}]\n",
+        "\n",
+        "response = engine.chat_completion(\n",
+        "    messages=messages,\n",
+        "    max_tokens=64,\n",
+        "    temperature=0.8,\n",
+        "    top_p=0.8,\n",
+        ")\n",
+        "\n",
+        "response"
+      ]
