+    {
+      "cell_type": "code",
+      "execution_count": null,
+      "metadata": {},
+      "outputs": [],
+      "source": [
+        "assistant_text = response[\"choices\"][0][\"message\"][\"content\"]\n",
+        "print(\"Dusty>\", assistant_text)"
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "markdown",
+      "metadata": {},
+      "source": [
+        "### 5.4 Short Context Windows for Tiny Models\n",
+        "\n",
+        "\n",
+        "Dusty is only about 8M parameters, so the default chat history window is intentionally tiny: `max_chat_turns=1`. That keeps the current user request from being diluted by old conversation tokens. Larger SFT profiles, such as SmolLM2-based models, can use a larger window."
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "code",
+      "execution_count": null,
+      "metadata": {},
+      "outputs": [],
+      "source": [
+        "print(\"Profile:\", engine.profile_name)\n",
+        "print(\"Default max_chat_turns:\", engine.spec.max_chat_turns)\n",
+        "\n",
+        "history = [\n",
+        "    {\"role\": \"system\", \"content\": \"Answer as Dusty, a tiny vacuum robot.\"},\n",
+        "    {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"what is under the couch?\"},\n",
+        "    {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": \"crumbs. many crumbs.\"},\n",
+        "    {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"should you go there?\"},\n",
+        "]\n",
+        "\n",
+        "response = engine.chat_completion(history, max_tokens=128)\n",
+        "print(\"Default window:\", response[\"choices\"][0][\"message\"][\"content\"])\n",
+        "\n",
+        "response = engine.chat_completion(history, max_tokens=128, max_chat_turns=2)\n",
+        "print(\"Two-turn window:\", response[\"choices\"][0][\"message\"][\"content\"])"
+      ]
+    },
+    {
+      "cell_type": "markdown",
+      "metadata": {},
+      "source": [
+        "### 5.5 The dustylm SDK\n",
+        "\n",
+        "You just loaded the raw `.pt` weights, instantiated the `nn.Module`, and wrote the token-by-token generation loop from scratch. That is exactly how the engine works under the hood.\n",
+        "\n",
+        "However, in a production environment, you don't want to rewrite that boilerplate every time you need to chat with your model. To solve this, we wrapped the exact logic you just learned into a lightweight Python package.\n",
+        "\n",
+        "Now, you can run the model in just two lines. The SDK works with your own local checkpoints and with published Hub models:\n",
+        "\n",
+        "```python\n",
+        "from dustylm import DustyLM\n",
